<!--
README — Deploy this static homepage to GitHub Pages (step-by-step)

Files: This single file (index.html) contains the full static homepage (HTML, CSS, JS).

Option A — (easiest) Deploy using the GitHub web interface (no programming needed)
1. Create a GitHub account at https://github.com if you don't have one.
2. Click the + (top-right) → New repository.
   - Repository name: e.g. my-fashion-store
   - Visibility: Public
   - Do NOT initialize with README (optional). Click Create repository.
3. On the new repo page, click Add file → Upload files.
4. Drag & drop this file (index.html) OR copy-paste its content using Add file → Create new file and paste.
   - Commit changes (leave message "Initial commit").
5. Go to Settings → Pages (left sidebar or under "Code and automation" → Pages).
   - Under "Build and deployment" select: Branch: main (or master) and folder: /(root).
   - Click Save.
6. After saving, you will see a "Site published at" URL. The public URL will be:
   https://<your-github-username>.github.io/<repo-name>/
   - If you name the repo exactly <your-github-username>.github.io then your site will be:
     https://<your-github-username>.github.io/

Option B — Upload with GitHub Desktop (no terminal knowledge needed)
1. Install GitHub Desktop (desktop.github.com) and sign in to your GitHub account.
2. File → New repository → fill name (my-fashion-store) → Create repository.
3. Copy this index.html into the repository folder on your computer.
4. In GitHub Desktop you will see the changed file; write commit message "Initial commit" → Commit to main → Push origin.
5. Then enable Pages as in Option A (Settings → Pages) and choose branch main / folder root.

Option C — Command line (for the few who want it)
1. Create a repo on GitHub (see Option A step 2).
2. On your computer, put index.html in a folder, then run:

   git init
   git add index.html
   git commit -m "Initial commit"
   git branch -M main
   git remote add origin https://github.com/<your-username>/<repo-name>.git
   git push -u origin main

3. Enable Pages in Settings → Pages and select branch main / root.

Quick troubleshooting tips
- Make repository public if you want others to see it.
- Make sure index.html is at the repository root (not inside a sub-folder), and that you picked the right branch when enabling Pages.
- If you change the file later, just update the file in the repo (upload new file or edit in GitHub UI) and commit — the published site will update automatically.

Custom domain
- You can use your own domain by adding a CNAME file or configuring the Pages section.

Need help?
- If you'd like, tell me your GitHub username and I can give the exact URL you'll get (or guide you through each click while you're at the GitHub screen).

----
Below is the full static homepage (one file). Save it as index.html and upload to GitHub as explained above.
-->

